        output='Based on the provided text, here is the breakdown of the common-control accounting treatment, its effect on historical financials, and how it differs from standard purchase accounting.\n\n### 1. Common-Control Accounting Treatment & Effect on Historical Financials\nBecause Elon Musk held a controlling financial interest (majority voting interest) in SpaceX, xAI, and X during all presented periods, the mergers were not treated as standard arm\'s-length acquisitions. Instead, they were accounted for as **reorganizations of entities under common control**, which constitutes a "change in reporting entity."\n\n**How it affects the historical financials:**\n*   **Retrospective Combination:** The consolidated financial statements are recast to combine the net assets and historical results of SpaceX, xAI, and X for *all periods presented*, as if they had always been a single combined entity.\n*   **Historical Carrying Amounts:** The net assets of the acquired entities are combined at their historical book values (carrying amounts) rather than being revalued.\n*   **No Goodwill or Intangibles:** The text explicitly notes that *no new goodwill or other intangible assets* have been recorded as a result of the mergers.\n*   **Elimination of Related-Party Transactions:** All historical transactions between SpaceX, xAI, and X that were previously considered "related-party" are retroactively eliminated in consolidation.\n*   **Retroactive Share Count Adjustments:** Historical common stock share counts for X and xAI are retroactively adjusted using the merger exchange ratios (and the 2026 five-for-one stock split) so that all historical common shares are presented as SpaceX Common Stock equivalents.\n*   **Omission of Separate Financials:** Because the historical financials are fully recast to include xAI and X, the company is not required to provide separate, standalone financial statements for those acquired entities.\n*   *Nuance regarding Preferred Stock:* While common stock is recast retrospectively, **xAI Redeemable Convertible Preferred Stock** is an exception. Because it was a legally distinct equity class prior to the merger, it is presented in its historical legal form for prior periods and is only converted into SpaceX Common Stock *prospectively* in Q1 2026 (the period the merger actually occurred).\n\n---\n\n### 2. Common-Control Accounting vs. Purchase Accounting\nWhile the provided text does not explicitly use the term "purchase accounting" (also known as the acquisition method), it highlights the exact mechanics of common-control accounting by explicitly stating what it *does not* do. \n\nHere is how common-control accounting differs from a standard third-party purchase acquisition:\n\n| Feature | Common-Control Accounting (SpaceX/xAI/X Mergers) | Standard Purchase Accounting (Arm\'s-Length Acquisitions) |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| **Timeline of Consolidation** | **Retrospective:** Financials are recast for *all periods presented* as if the entities were always combined. | **Prospective:** The acquirer only includes the target\'s financial results from the exact date of acquisition forward. Prior historical periods are *not* restated. |\n| **Asset & Liability Valuation** | **Historical Carrying Amounts:** Assets and liabilities are transferred at their existing historical book values. | **Fair Value:** Assets and liabilities are "stepped up" or "stepped down" to their fair market value on the acquisition date. |\n| **Goodwill & Intangibles** | **None:** The text explicitly states *no new goodwill or other intangible assets* are recorded. | **Recognized:** Goodwill is typically created if the purchase price exceeds the fair value of the net identifiable assets. New intangible assets are also recognized. |\n| **Nature of Transaction** | Viewed as an internal **reorganization** or restructuring of entities already under the same ultimate boss. | Viewed as an **acquisition** of a new, unrelated business from a third party. |\n| **Equity Treatment** | Historical equity of both entities is combined and adjusted by exchange ratios to reflect a continuation of the historical entity. | The target company\'s historical equity is eliminated; the acquirer issues new shares or pays cash, and only the acquirer\'s historical equity remains. |',
