        output='Based on the provided prospectus excerpts, here is a detailed breakdown of what the filing says regarding the mergers with xAI and X Holdings, the retrospective recasting of financials, and the overall basis of presentation.\n\n### 1. Mergers with xAI and X Holdings\nThe filing details a two-step consolidation of Elon Musk’s AI and social media ventures into SpaceX, both of which were executed as share exchanges and accounted for as **reorganizations of entities under common control** (since Musk held majority voting interest in all entities involved).\n\n*   **The X Merger (March 28, 2025):** xAI acquired X Holdings Corp. (“X”) and X.AI Corp., making them wholly-owned subsidiaries of xAI. \n    *   *Conversion Ratios:* X Common Stock converted into 2.776 shares of xAI Common Stock. X.AI Corp. Common and Preferred Stock converted on a 1:1 basis into xAI Common and xAI Redeemable Convertible Preferred Stock.\n*   **The xAI Merger (February 2, 2026):** SpaceX acquired X.AI Holdings Corp. (“xAI”), making it a wholly-owned subsidiary of SpaceX.\n    *   *Consideration:* SpaceX issued 321.7 million Class A shares, 121.7 million Class B shares (on a pre-split basis), and paid $2.947 billion in cash to xAI stockholders.\n    *   *Conversion Ratios:* xAI Common Stock converted into SpaceX Common Stock at a fixed exchange ratio of **0.1433** SpaceX shares per xAI share. Eligible service providers were given a cash election option of $75.46 per share.\n    *   *Warrants:* Outstanding xAI customer warrants triggered an acceleration clause, automatically exercising on a cashless basis into SpaceX Class A Common Stock at the 0.1433 ratio.\n*   **Tesla’s Investment:** In January 2026, Tesla agreed to invest $2 billion in xAI Series E Preferred Stock. Following the xAI Merger and regulatory approvals, this right converted into SpaceX Class A Common Stock, resulting in SpaceX issuing 3.8 million shares to Tesla in March 2026.\n*   **2026 Stock Split:** On May 4, 2026, SpaceX executed a 5-for-1 forward stock split of its Class A, B, and C Common Stock. \n\n### 2. Retrospective Recast\nBecause the mergers were between entities under common control, SpaceX was required to retrospectively recast its financial statements to present the companies as if they had always been combined. \n\n*   **Historical Combination:** The consolidated financial statements reflect the retrospective combination of the net assets of SpaceX, xAI, and X at their **historical carrying amounts** for all periods presented. \n*   **Eliminations & Goodwill:** No new goodwill or intangible assets were recorded as a result of the mergers. All historical related-party transactions between SpaceX, xAI, and X have been eliminated in consolidation.\n*   **Common Stock Recast:** Historical X, X.AI Corp., and xAI Common Stock are presented in the historical financial statements as if they had been converted into SpaceX Common Stock at the applicable exchange rates for all periods presented.\n*   **Exception for xAI Preferred Stock:** xAI Redeemable Convertible Preferred Stock is **not** retrospectively recast on an as-converted basis prior to the merger date. Because it was a legally distinct equity class of a predecessor entity, historical balance sheets continue to reflect it as outstanding xAI Preferred Stock. The conversion into SpaceX Common Stock is only recognized prospectively in the period the merger actually occurred (Q1 2026).\n*   **Stock Split Adjustment:** All historical share and per-share information has been retroactively adjusted to reflect the May 2026 5-for-1 stock split.\n*   **Change in Reporting Entity:** This retrospective combination constitutes a "change in reporting entity." Consequently, separate financial statements for xAI and X are not provided.\n\n### 3. Basis of Presentation\nThe financial statements and accompanying notes establish the foundational accounting rules and operational scope of the newly combined entity.\n\n*   **U.S. GAAP & Consolidation:** The financials are prepared in accordance with U.S. Generally Accepted Accounting Principles (GAAP). They include the accounts of SpaceX and its wholly-owned subsidiaries, with all intercompany balances and transactions eliminated.\n*   **Use of Estimates:** Preparation requires management to make significant estimates and assumptions that affect reported assets, liabilities, revenues, and expenses. Key areas of judgment include cost-to-cost revenue recognition, deferred tax valuation allowances, inventory reserves, and the fair value/useful lives of goodwill and indefinite-lived intangibles.\n*   **Operational Scope (Segments):** The basis of presentation now encompasses SpaceX\'s core aerospace and Starlink connectivity operations, alongside a new **AI segment**. This AI segment operates a vertically integrated platform spanning the Grok frontier LLM, enterprise/consumer AI solutions, computational infrastructure, and the X platform (described as a "real-time information, entertainment, and free speech platform").\n*   **Limitations of Historical Data:** The filing explicitly cautions that the summary historical consolidated financial and operating data (which now includes the combined footprint of SpaceX, xAI, and X) is not necessarily indicative of future results or full fiscal periods.',
