    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='Based on the provided excerpts from the prospectus and financial statement notes, here is the breakdown of how the company handles goodwill, intangible assets, fair value step-ups, purchase price allocations, and the specific accounting treatments for its major acquisitions.\n\n### 1. Common-Control Accounting & What is NOT Recorded\nThe acquisitions of **xAI** (by SpaceX in Feb 2026) and **X / Twitter** (by xAI in March 2025) were accounted for as **reorganizations of entities under common control**, because Elon Musk held a controlling financial/majority voting interest in all entities involved. \n\nBecause of this specific accounting treatment, the following are **NOT recorded**:\n*   **No Fair Value Step-Up:** The net assets of xAI and X were *not* marked up to their current fair market values. Instead, the consolidated financial statements reflect a retrospective combination of the entities\' net assets at their **historical carrying amounts** (historical cost).\n*   **No Purchase Price Allocation:** Because the assets and liabilities simply carry over at their historical book values, a traditional purchase price allocation (assigning fair values to acquired assets and liabilities) was not performed for these mergers.\n*   **No New Goodwill or Intangibles:** The filing explicitly states: *"No new goodwill or other intangible assets have been recorded"* as a result of the xAI and X mergers. \n*   **Eliminations:** All historical related-party transactions between SpaceX, xAI, and X were eliminated in consolidation.\n\n### 2. Goodwill\n*   **Definition & Policy:** Goodwill represents the excess of the purchase price over the fair value of identifiable assets and assumed liabilities in a standard business combination. It is not amortized but is tested for impairment annually (October 1) or when triggering events occur.\n*   **Balances & Allocation:** As of March 31, 2026, total goodwill was **$11,681 million**. It is heavily concentrated in the AI segment:\n    *   **AI Segment:** $11,166 million\n    *   **Connectivity Segment:** $515 million\n*   **Impairment:** The company conducted annual tests and noted that **no goodwill impairments** were identified for the years ended December 31, 2023, 2024, and 2025.\n\n### 3. Intangible Assets\n*   **The "X" Rebranding Impairment:** In 2023, the company rebranded Twitter to X. This triggered an impairment assessment, resulting in a massive **$3,775 million impairment charge** on the previously indefinite-lived brand intangible (attributed to the AI segment). Consequently, the brand was reclassified as a **finite-lived intangible asset** with a 5-year useful life, valued using the relief-from-royalty method.\n*   **Indefinite-Lived Intangibles:** As of March 31, 2026, the company held $19 million in indefinite-lived intangibles, consisting primarily of trade names and domain names.\n*   **Pending Spectrum Acquisition:** In September 2025, the company entered into a Spectrum License Purchase Agreement with EchoStar (total consideration involving billions in cash and debt satisfaction). Because the transaction has not yet closed (expected Nov 2027), it is not yet on the balance sheet, but the filing notes that once it closes, the spectrum licenses will be recognized as **acquired intangible assets**.\n\n### 4. Fair Value Step-Up & Purchase Price Allocation\n*   **Absence in Mergers:** As detailed in Section 1, fair value step-ups and purchase price allocations are entirely absent regarding the SpaceX/xAI/X mergers due to the common-control accounting rules (ASC 805-50), which mandate the use of historical carrying amounts rather than fair value.\n*   **Application of Fair Value Elsewhere:** While not used for M&A step-ups in this context, the company strictly applies the **ASC 820 Fair Value Hierarchy (Levels I, II, and III)** to other areas of its balance sheet:\n    *   **Digital Assets (Bitcoin):** Measured at fair value on a recurring basis using Level I inputs (quoted prices on active exchanges). As of Dec 31, 2025, the company held 18,712 Bitcoin with a cost basis of $661 million and a fair value of $1,637 million.\n    *   **Impairment Testing:** Fair value (using discounted cash flows and market approaches) is used to test reporting units and indefinite-lived intangibles for impairment.\n    *   **Financial Instruments:** Cash equivalents, marketable securities, and restricted cash are measured at fair value based on observable market data (Levels I and II).',
