        output='Based on the provided excerpts from the S-1 prospectus, here is what the filing reveals regarding standalone SpaceX operations, pre-merger financials, and the limitations of the historical financial statements:\n\n### 1. Standalone SpaceX Operations (Space & Connectivity)\nBefore the integration of xAI and X, SpaceX’s core operations consisted of two primary segments, which the filing details extensively:\n*   **Space Segment:** Focuses on designing, manufacturing, and launching reusable rockets (Falcon and Starship). It achieved sustained positive Segment Adjusted EBITDA starting in **2018**. In 2025, the Space segment generated an operating loss of $(657) million but achieved a Segment Adjusted EBITDA of $653 million (which included the impact of funding $3,004 million in R&D). Operationally, it completed 170 missions in 2025 and launched over 2,200 metric tons to orbit (over 80% of the global mass to orbit for the year).\n*   **Connectivity Segment (Starlink):** Operates the low-Earth orbit satellite broadband network. It was funded initially by the Space segment\'s EBITDA and external equity, and it achieved sustained positive Segment Adjusted EBITDA starting in **2023**. As of March 31, 2026, it had approximately 9,600 satellites and 10.3 million subscribers across 164 markets.\n*   **Capital Allocation Strategy:** The filing highlights a "stellar track record" of using cash flows from the foundational Space segment to fund the Connectivity segment, creating a flywheel of predictable, recurring revenue. \n\n### 2. Pre-Merger Financials & Accounting Treatment\nBecause the acquisitions of X.AI Holdings (effective Feb 2, 2026) and X Holdings (effective March 28, 2025) were considered **transactions between entities under common control**, the financials do not look like a standard M&A acquisition:\n*   **Retrospective Recasting:** The consolidated financial statements have been retrospectively recast for *all periods presented* to combine the historical results of SpaceX, xAI, and X. \n*   **No New Goodwill:** The assets and liabilities of the merged entities were combined at their historical carrying amounts. No new goodwill or intangible assets were recorded.\n*   **Stock Split Adjustment:** A 5-for-1 stock split that occurred on May 4, 2026, has also been retroactively adjusted across all historical share and per-share data presented in the filing.\n*   **Elimination of Internal Transactions:** All historical related-party transactions between SpaceX, xAI, and X prior to the mergers have been eliminated in consolidation.\n\n### 3. What Investors *Cannot* Observe from the Historical Financials\nThe filing includes several explicit warnings and accounting caveats about what the historical data obscures or fails to represent:\n*   **Future Predictive Value:** The summary historical consolidated financial and operating data is **not indicative of the results to be expected for any future period**, nor are interim results necessarily indicative of full-year results.\n*   **An "As-Converted" Historical View of xAI Preferred Stock:** Although xAI’s Redeemable Convertible Preferred Stock converted into SpaceX Common Stock upon the merger, the historical balance sheets **are not recast on an as-converted basis**. Because it was a legally distinct class of equity prior to the merger, it is presented in its historical legal form. Investors cannot observe the "as-converted" historical impact; the conversion is only recognized prospectively in Q1 2026.\n*   **Standalone (Unmerged) SpaceX Financials:** Because the financials are retrospectively combined under common control accounting, investors cannot look at the primary consolidated financial statements and easily isolate the strict, legally standalone historical financials of SpaceX (excluding xAI and X) prior to the mergers. \n*   **Historical Related-Party Friction:** Because all historical related-party transactions between the commonly controlled entities (SpaceX, xAI, and X) were eliminated in consolidation, investors cannot observe the historical scale, pricing, or financial impact of the internal dealings between these entities before they were formally merged.',
